though their work is completely

00:02:22.130 --> 00:02:24.960
different just because they were
from the same place and they ended

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:29.950
up living next-door to each
other in Mexico City in exile.

00:02:29.950 --> 00:02:32.560
So what I'm going to
propose to do here today goes

00:02:32.560 --> 00:02:37.200 position:56%
against that tradition of constantly
comparing Mutis and Garcia Marquez.

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:41.740
I'm actually going to do a sort of
literary contrapuntal or a point

00:02:41.740 --> 00:02:47.180
and counter point that compares
not Mutis and Garcia Marquez,

00:02:47.180 --> 00:02:51.350
but actually Mutis and
Miguel de Cervantes,

00:02:51.350 --> 00:02:55.230
perhaps a much more
surprising comparison.

00:02:55.230 --> 00:02:59.930
So I've chosen this musical
contrapuntal structure

00:02:59.930 --> 00:03:02.050
for a couple of reasons.

00:03:02.050 --> 00:03:06.350
First, the juxtaposition
between Cervantes and Mutis,

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:08.790
who is shown here with
a cocktail which I love.

00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:14.460
I hope my next book has a name of
a cocktail in the author photo.

00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:20.160
So in comparing these two great
authors I want to pay homage

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:23.500
to Mutis and really put him on
the same level with Cervantes,

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:26.060
which I think is a bold claim.

00:03:26.060 --> 00:03:31.160
Second, I am paying a very
personal tribute to Edith Grossman

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:36.330
who is the translator of adventures
and misadventures of Maqroll,

00:03:36.330 --> 00:03:39.660 position:56%
as well as Don Quixote by Cervantes.

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:41.990
And so as Catalina
mentioned, you have the chance

00:03:41.990 --> 00:03:46.950
to buy the Adventures of Maqroll,
which is Edith's translation.

00:03:46.950 --> 00:03:50.920
But the last and most
important reason why I want

00:03:50.920 --> 00:03:54.950
to compare these two authors is
that there are many affinities

00:03:54.950 --> 00:04:01.130
between Mutis and Cervantes
both biographical and literary.

00:04:01.130 --> 00:04:04.220
This is so much the case that I
think that Mutis actually wrote

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:07.640
with Cervantes in mind and I'm
going to point out a couple

00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:10.680
of places here today where I
think we can see Mutis thinking

00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:12.600
about Cervantes.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:17.250
So this contrapuntal is designed
to highlight those enduring values

00:04:17.250 --> 00:04:21.620
and the contemporary
relevance of Alvaro Mutis.

00:04:21.620 --> 00:04:24.210
Also, I really just want to
provide points of departure

00:04:24.210 --> 00:04:25.520
for our question-and-answer period

00:04:25.520 --> 00:04:28.540
because I think that's always
the most illuminating part

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:30.400
of the talk for me.

00:04:30.400 --> 00:04:35.650
So to begin due to these accidents
of birth should state the obvious

00:04:35.650 --> 00:04:40.130
and these two men clearly belong
to different nations and eras.

00:04:40.130 --> 00:04:46.330
But Alvaro Mutis was born in
Bogota in Columbia in 1923.

00:04:46.330 --> 00:04:50.460
He took up residence in
Mexico City in the late 1950's

00:04:50.460 --> 00:04:54.620
where he died on September
22nd, 2013.

00:04:54.620 --> 00:04:56.210
So this is also really a tribute

00:04:56.210 --> 00:05:00.080
to him just a few short
years after his passing.

00:05:00.080 --> 00:05:03.860
So and of course, I'm sure most of
you know Cervantes lived in Spain

00:05:03.860 --> 00:05:06.940
and died in Madrid in 1616.

00:05:06.940 --> 00:05:11.280
But despite these differences, the
men share biographical elements

00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:13.420
that marked their literary
production.

00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:15.610
So I'll give you just
a few examples.

00:05:15.610 --> 00:05:21.190
First, both authors showed a really
early preference for writing poetry

00:05:21.190 --> 00:05:24.430
and a penchant for more
colorful activities.

00:05:24.430 --> 00:05:27.810
Cervantes once wounded
a man in a dual

00:05:27.810 --> 00:05:32.230
and Alvaro spent his
free time playing pool,

00:05:32.230 --> 00:05:35.230
so much so that he actually
never graduated from high school

00:05:35.230 --> 00:05:36.530
because he spent a lot of time

00:05:36.530 --> 00:05:38.920
in the billiard hall
and reading novels.

00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:41.600
He said Dickens was
one of his favorites.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:46.000
More importantly, the sea also
plays a large role in the work

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.420
of both men and their lives.

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:55.310
Cervantes famously lost an arm in
the 1571 naval battle of Lepanto,

00:05:55.310 --> 00:05:58.900
which earned him the epithet
El Manco de Lepanto, you know,

00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:01.720
the one armed man from Lepanto.

00:06:01.720 --> 00:06:06.170
Now in a less military way water
imagery is an essential part

00:06:06.170 --> 00:06:09.480
of Mutis' prose in poetry.

00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:12.210
Throughout this talk I'm
going to point out a couple

00:06:12.210 --> 00:06:16.490
of aquatic motifs, I think
that really marked Mutis.

00:06:16.490 --> 00:06:20.120
And we're going to start
doing that by listening to one

00:06:20.120 --> 00:06:23.200 position:56%
of Mutis' poems that features water.

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:26.860
So you're going to have to bear
with me here as I sneak out.

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:30.500
We're going to listen to
a poem called Nocturno,

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:31.900
there it'll show here.

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:37.400 position:56%
So this poem is called Nocturno from
