00:08:18.770 --> 00:08:23.130
falling over the coffee
plants in the poem

00:08:23.130 --> 00:08:27.500 position:56%
and that brings a very cleansing
[foreign language] knowing the words

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:29.960
of Mutis.

00:08:29.960 --> 00:08:34.270
So water also appears in
Mutis' prose, you know,

00:08:34.270 --> 00:08:38.530
always as a cleansing
or liberating image.

00:08:38.530 --> 00:08:44.700 position:56%
In fact, Mutis' most famous literary
character is also a sailor right.

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:49.970
The peripatetic and melancholic
mariner named Maqroll el Gaviero.

00:08:49.970 --> 00:08:53.920
And I think that there is
a great similarity there,

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:56.740
actually between Cervantes
and Mutis in the sense

00:08:56.740 --> 00:08:59.790
that both men created a literary

00:08:59.790 --> 00:09:03.470
or a fictional person
who outlives them right.

00:09:03.470 --> 00:09:07.230
You all know about Don Quixote
he's become an iconic figure,

00:09:07.230 --> 00:09:12.340
but I argue that Mutis' character
Maqroll should be just as famous.

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:16.410
So Maqroll appears in a series
of seven short novels collected

00:09:16.410 --> 00:09:18.400
in English as we mentioned
as the Adventures

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:20.440
and Misadventures of Maqroll.

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:26.220 position:56%
And in those novels the eponymous
protagonist travels the world right,

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:29.730 position:56%
on a variety of unsuccessful quests.

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:32.700
So I think you can see
some similarities already

00:09:32.700 --> 00:09:36.140
between Maqroll el
Gaviero and Don Quixote.

00:09:36.140 --> 00:09:37.940
But I think we should
go a bit deeper,

00:09:37.940 --> 00:09:43.800
so let's start looking very closely
at his name, Maqroll el Gaviero.

00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:46.510
Maqroll Mutis stated in lots

00:09:46.510 --> 00:09:49.590
of interviews is actually
his own invention,

00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:53.920 position:56%
it's a made-up name though he wanted
to give a vaguely Scottish flavor,

00:09:53.920 --> 00:09:56.660
which you can hear with
the Maq in the Maqroll.

00:09:56.660 --> 00:10:01.670
Yet Maqroll is also intended to
be of inscrutable origin right.

00:10:01.670 --> 00:10:04.940
Mutis never reveals
his country of birth.

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:09.880 position:56%
He speaks multiple languages and the
reader learns only that he traveled

00:10:09.880 --> 00:10:12.590
on a fake passport
from Cypress right.

00:10:12.590 --> 00:10:16.420
So it gives you an idea of a
shady past in his background.

00:10:16.420 --> 00:10:21.290 position:56%
In reality, I like to argue that his
[foreign language] is the sea right.

00:10:21.290 --> 00:10:27.510
Now his nickname el Gaviero is also
an explicitly nautical reference.

00:10:27.510 --> 00:10:30.770
The gavia in Spanish
means the jib right,

00:10:30.770 --> 00:10:33.330
it's one of the sails
on a large ship.

00:10:33.330 --> 00:10:37.460
And the gaviero is the
sailor who manages it often

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:40.910
from a very high point
up on the mast right,

00:10:40.910 --> 00:10:43.340
so it's kind of a lookout
point as well.

00:10:43.340 --> 00:10:47.250
So in her translation Edie Grossman
has very ghastly rendered Maqroll's

00:10:47.250 --> 00:10:50.630
nickname el gaviero as the lookout.

00:10:50.630 --> 00:10:54.080
A title that refers explicitly
to that sailor who perches

00:10:54.080 --> 00:11:00.150
up on the crow's nest of the ship
and scans the horizon for dangers.

00:11:00.150 --> 00:11:05.360
In fact, this position at the top
of the mast was also known formerly

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:11.020
as the carajo if you'll excuse my
rather vulgar language here okay.

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:15.330
So being in the carajo was
not very highly desired

00:11:15.330 --> 00:11:17.540
because of the wind and the rain.

00:11:17.540 --> 00:11:20.460
And that and this may
be a folk etymology,

00:11:20.460 --> 00:11:22.280
but as far as I've been
able to tell that post,

00:11:22.280 --> 00:11:28.720
that nautical post gave rise to
the expression vete el carajo,

00:11:28.720 --> 00:11:33.710
which now has the meaning that all
of you are thinking of right now.

00:11:33.710 --> 00:11:38.230
So when we take these two aspects
of the name together Maqroll

00:11:38.230 --> 00:11:44.690 position:56%
and gaviero evokes a traveler with
a capacity for self-invention right.

00:11:44.690 --> 00:11:47.990
He's employed in a rather
antiquated profession

00:11:47.990 --> 00:11:52.030
and he contemplates the
vastness of the ocean

00:11:52.030 --> 00:11:54.950
and the depths of human folly.

00:11:54.950 --> 00:11:58.120
So Maqroll and Don Quixote
in this counterpoint

00:11:58.120 --> 00:12:00.410
that I'm doing are
actually very similar.

00:12:00.410 --> 00:12:06.590 position:56%
If we remember that Alonzo Quijano
also invents himself as Don Quixote.

00:12:06.590 --> 00:12:09.340
He too takes up an
antiquated profession right,

00:12:09.340 --> 00:12:12.220
that of knight errant
and he also travels

00:12:12.220 --> 00:12:15.730
over the vast landscape
of La Mancha.

00:12:15.730 --> 00:12:18.210
In another sense I think that
both characters are really

00:12:18.210 --> 00:12:22.190
from nowhere right, in the sense
that Maqroll has no fixed home.

00:12:22.190 --> 00:12:26.090
Don Quixote is from La Mancha,
which is so arid and boring

00:12:26.090 --> 00:12:28.500
that it's like being from nowhere.

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:31.370
But I think great things
can come from nowhere.

00:12:31.370 --> 00:12:35.520
And each character always sets out
right to perform these great feats

00:12:35.520 --> 00:12:39.870
and so that's what makes them
similar in their uniqueness.

00:12:39.870 --> 00:12:43.540
So let's turn back
now to our authors.

00:12:43.540 --> 00:12:47.490
The most significant biographical
similarity between Cervantes

00:12:47.490 --> 00:12:53.380
and Mutis is they both spent a
formative period of time in jail.

00:12:53.380 --> 00:12:56.050
They were imprisoned for what
we would call today white-collar

00:12:56.050 --> 00:12:57.630
crimes right.

00:12:57.630 --> 00:13:02.430
Cervantes was involved in
disputes in his very odious job

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:07.920
as a tax collector and as a result
he was incarcerated several times.

00:13:07.920 --> 00:13:13.000
In 1956, Mutis was working in
public relations for Standard Oil,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.840
which is now known as Exxon.

00:13:15.840 --> 00:13:21.260
When he was accused of embezzling
company funds he fled to Mexico.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:24.340
And from there Mutis fought
the extradition process back

00:13:24.340 --> 00:13:29.730 position:56%
to Columbia, but the Mexican
officials detained him for 15 months

00:13:29.730 --> 00:13:33.230
in what is known as the --
oh sorry, there's the books

00:13:33.230 --> 00:13:34.690
that we're working with here.

00:13:34.690 --> 00:13:38.540
So he was detained for 15
months in the black palace

00:13:38.540 --> 00:13:42.050
of the Lecumberri also
known as El Palacios Negro.

00:13:42.050 --> 00:13:44.560
It's one of the most notorious,

00:13:44.560 --> 00:13:47.770
it was one of the most
notorious prisons in Mexico.

00:13:47.770 --> 00:13:52.560
And since 1978 it's actually
housed the archives in Mexico,

00:13:52.560 --> 00:13:56.570
so I think there's an amazing
coincidence there between writing

00:13:56.570 --> 00:14:02.210 position:56%
in the written word and
imprisonment, which often gives rise

00:14:02.210 --> 00:14:04.790 position:56%
to really great works of literature.

00:14:04.790 --> 00:14:09.150
So the charges against
Mutis were later dropped

00:14:09.150 --> 00:14:13.800
and they were largely attributed
to the political wrangling

00:14:13.800 --> 00:14:18.340
of the Colombian dictator,
Gustavo Rojas Pinilla at the time.

00:14:18.340 --> 00:14:22.600
But nevertheless, Mutis spent 15
months in Lecumberri and I think

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:27.790
that that had a very powerful
effect on his later literature.

00:14:27.790 --> 00:14:31.120
So in fact, these harsh
experiences turned out to be a boon

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:33.960
for both men's literary creations.

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:37.730
Cervantes writes in the prologue
to part one of the Quixote

00:14:37.730 --> 00:14:40.190
that the idea for his
great work came to him

00:14:40.190 --> 00:14:41.680
in the jail of Seville right.

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:45.640
Any of you have seen The Man of
La Mancha the music you'll know

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:48.950
that it starts with
Cervantes in prison.

00:14:48.950 --> 00:14:51.710
But Mutis also found
inspiration there.

00:14:51.710 --> 00:14:56.260
He published a few short vignettes
about his time in Lecumberri

00:14:56.260 --> 00:14:59.880
and it's called Lecumberri Diary.

00:14:59.880 --> 00:15:03.670
The best image that Moody's
Mutis creates in that diary is

00:15:03.670 --> 00:15:06.410
yet again an aquatic motif right.

00:15:06.410 --> 00:15:11.260
He envisions a torrential rain
similar to the one we heard earlier

00:15:11.260 --> 00:15:15.360
that will flood the prison
and it fills him with hope.

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:19.060
In this instance water imagery
indicates freedom right.

00:15:19.060 --> 00:15:22.900
Seas, rivers, rains all
symbolized liberty for Mutis.

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:27.250
And he hopes that it will
carry him out floating

00:15:27.250 --> 00:15:31.270
onto the vast floodwaters and it
will and I quote from the diary,

00:15:31.270 --> 00:15:36.990
leave behind judges,
ministers, scribes, guards,

00:15:36.990 --> 00:15:41.240
and all the other beasts
that cling to human flesh

00:15:41.240 --> 00:15:44.230
and blindly beat their
heads against us

00:15:44.230 --> 00:15:49.530
in a furious attempt to destroy us.

00:15:49.530 --> 00:15:54.000
So in the rest of his life's work
Mutis would deplore the injustice

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:58.110
and the incompetence of
bureaucratic ordeals.

00:15:58.110 --> 00:16:01.700
Cervantes similarly critiqued the
holy brotherhood and the suffering

00:16:01.700 --> 00:16:05.310
of the galley slaves in the
Quixote if we can recall.

00:16:05.310 --> 00:16:07.620
These bleak prison stints turned

00:16:07.620 --> 00:16:10.030
out to be what Mutis calls [foreign
language] okay [foreign language].

00:16:10.030 --> 00:16:13.810
Fertile misery for both men

00:16:13.810 --> 00:16:22.390 position:56%
because their novels exhibit a very
deep sympathy for single individuals

00:16:22.390 --> 00:16:26.580
and an equally deep skepticism
towards the possibility

00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:30.470
of justice in human society.

00:16:30.470 --> 00:16:34.810
So in addition to formative
prison time both men turned away

00:16:34.810 --> 00:16:38.640
from poetry and towards prose
very late in their life.

00:16:38.640 --> 00:16:41.260
In fact, their masterpieces
came when they were

00:16:41.260 --> 00:16:43.520
in their late 50's and early 60's.

00:16:43.520 --> 00:16:48.300
Cervantes was 58 when he published
the Quixote, Mutis was in his 60's

00:16:48.300 --> 00:16:52.790
and retired from publicity work
at that multinational corporation

00:16:52.790 --> 00:16:55.820
