long before Cervantes himself,

00:50:11.280 --> 00:50:12.580
that's his own [inaudible].

00:50:12.580 --> 00:50:20.480
But it seems like the novels
are very much about [inaudible].

00:50:20.480 --> 00:50:28.770
And it's interesting to think about
the idea of the nation as Mutis

00:50:28.770 --> 00:50:33.810
as well because there
really isn't [inaudible].

00:50:37.210 --> 00:50:40.640
&gt;&gt; Charlotte Rogers:
No, no it's okay.

00:50:40.640 --> 00:50:46.720
I do think that Mutis is
famous for proclaiming himself

00:50:46.720 --> 00:50:48.920
to be monarchist whenever
he's asked about politics.

00:50:48.920 --> 00:50:55.560
And I think that idea comes
from his [foreign language] idea

00:50:55.560 --> 00:51:00.100
like that's why he says that
marriage is or prostitution is just

00:51:00.100 --> 00:51:02.930
as conventional as marriage right,
he wants to shock people and go

00:51:02.930 --> 00:51:06.030
against their accepted
idea of what's going on.

00:51:06.030 --> 00:51:08.880
I think he also wants to avoid
talking about politics there,

00:51:08.880 --> 00:51:12.450
especially living in
exile in Mexico City.

00:51:12.450 --> 00:51:17.510
I think he also wants to
echo Maqroll who for him was

00:51:17.510 --> 00:51:20.860
like another person in his life
when he says that he's living

00:51:20.860 --> 00:51:23.030
in a time that's alien
to his interest.

00:51:23.030 --> 00:51:27.980 position:56%
I think that's a crystallization and
perhaps exaggeration of that idea.

00:51:27.980 --> 00:51:32.730
So yeah, I mean Maqroll himself
is certainly against the notion

00:51:32.730 --> 00:51:36.880
of power dominating him right,
he wants to be a communist.

00:51:36.880 --> 00:51:38.550
But yeah, it's a good quote.

00:51:38.550 --> 00:51:40.540
So thank you.

